3. If both conditions are met, increment the count and update k.
4. Store the count in result[i].
5. Return the result array.

The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate through the queries array once. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single array to store the result for each query. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs a few operations and does not require any significant energy consumption.

